We recommended for the Municipal Mayor to:

1. Direct the MACCO to prepare the adjusting entries to recognize and reflect the understatement of the Drugs and Medicine Inventory account by P578,861.26, as at December 31, 2022;


2. Direct the MHO upon receipt of the vaccines, to submit immediately the Acknowledgment Receipt for In-Kind Donations along with the PTR to MACCO, and for the latter to record the COVID items on time. For the utilization, prepare also Issuance Form for In-Kind Donations and submit it to the MACCO within a reasonable time;

3. Instruct the MHO to create a system in coming up with timely report preparation and submission;

4. Enjoin the MHO and MACCO to secure the cost of the transferred vaccines if not indicated in the PTR from the Provincial Health Office;

We recommended that the Municipality properly plan their utilization and distribution of COVID-19 vaccines, including nearly expiring vaccines, to prevent wastage thereof. Moreover, the management should ensure that the data reported in the VORS is accurate and complete; and

We recommended to ensure the proper disposal of COVID-19 vaccine in accordance with the proper guidelines. Additionally, pending the retrieval of the vaccines or reverse logistics, the vaccines should be safely kept in a separate area to prevent people and other medical inventories from any possible exposure to infectious waste or potential health risks.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:           

• Municipal Treasurer and other officials concerned to undertake effective, efficient, and aggressive tax collection strategies to improve collection. Prepare and served NDs for all delinquent RPUs, and prioritize those which are more than 10 years delinquent, If possible, coordinate with other offices that are regularly conducting field inspections, to help them in the distribution of NDs;

• Municipal Assessor to review the assessment rolls as it appears that several RPUs under the Republic of the Philippines were still assessed and computed with tax due. Coordinate with the Provincial Assessor on correcting the said records in the ETRACS;

• Municipal Treasurer to conduct dialogue with the owners of the RPUs under CARP to address concerns on collection of taxes. If warranted, request the presence of the Provincial Treasurer and Provincial Legal Officer to assist in such undertaking.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor together with the Municipal Assessor make representation with the Provincial Governor, Provincial Legal Officer, and Provincial Assessor to discuss and eventually settle those RPUs with boundary conflict, to ensure that the collection of taxes for these properties will be made by the appropriate LGU and the income derived therefrom will accrue to their account.

For the delinquent real property taxes with NDs already served, we recommend the management impose the legal remedies either by administrative auction thru levy on real property or judicial action, following the procedures authorized in the LGC, to enforce collection and to undertake the same expeditiously on a yearly basis to reduce amounts accumulated as receivables for delinquent taxes.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the MSWDO to: 

Require the LGU workers to refund the amount received or if indeed the names pertain to different individuals, submit certification stating such circumstances, otherwise, the same shall be charged to those responsible for their inclusion;  

For barangay functionaries, submit barangay certification that such individuals belong to a low-income family, does not belong to a 4Ps household, and none of the member(s) of his/her family falls within the exclusion; 

Require those private employees to submit certification from their respective employers/DOLE that 1) they are “no work no pay” during the ECQ periods; and 2) that they did not receive any cash subsidy under the DOLE amelioration program for private employees;

