Recommendations:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the MSWDO to:
Submit justification on the 6,197 mis-targeted SAP cash subsidy beneficiaries as to the 376 with wrong supporting documents based on their status; 5,558 with lacking data presented in their SAC forms; and as to the 263 unqualified beneficiaries;
For Indigenous People (IPs) beneficiaries, submit Certification from NCIP or the tribal chieftain/council of elders that the beneficiaries are IPs and are on subsistence economy;
Require the LGU workers to refund the amount received or if indeed the names pertain to different individuals, submit certification stating such circumstances, otherwise, the same shall be charged to those responsible for their inclusion;
For barangay functionaries, submit barangay certification that such individuals belongs to a low-income family, does not belong to a 4Ps household, and none of the member(s) of his/her family falls within the exclusion;
Require the those private employees to submit certification from their respective employers/DOLE that 1) they are “no work no pay” during the ECQ periods; and 2) that they did not receive any cash subsidy under the DOLE amelioration program for private employees;
Require those individual/household receiving twice to refund the amount received otherwise, the same shall be charged to those responsible for their inclusion;
Conduct barangay-to-barangay campaigns to encourage those under the vulnerable sectors (i.e. PWD, Solo-Parents, Senior Citizens) to register and secure appropriate ID from the MSWDO for them to be able to conveniently access government’s services accorded to them;
Maintain an updated database of the municipality’s residents through better coordination with Puroks and Barangays to properly identify possible beneficiaries of social amelioration programs of the government and expedite the delivery of the same.

We recommended that the responsible officials and employees of the Municipality observe prudence in the discharge of their duties so as government funds are appropriately safeguarded through the following measures:

In case a Letter of Credit is issued by the Municipality, the BAC should ensure that the requirements of Section 42.6 of the Revised IRR of the R.A. No. 9184 are fully observed and if the winning bidder is a local supplier, the LC should be issued to the latter and not to its foreign manufacturer or supplier;

No payment shall be made on a Letter of Credit unless the goods have been delivered and accepted as certified by the Municipality in accordance with the delivery schedule provided for in the contract;

The Municipal Accounting Office and the Municipal Treasurer’s Office submit a written explanation on the non-imposition of liquidated damages on the delays committed by the supplier and collect the same from the supplier;

The Municipal Treasurer’s Office should submit the following lacking documents:
For imported items:
Home Consumption Value of the items
Breakdown of the expenses incurred in the Importation
Original copy of Dealer’s/Supplier’s Invoices showing the quantity, description of the articles, unit and total value, duly signed by the dealer or his representative, and indicating receipt by the proper agency official of items delivered.
Tax receipts from the Bureau of Customs or the BIR indicating the exact specifications and/or serial number of the equipment procured by the government as proof of payment of all taxes and duties due on the same equipment, supplied or sold to the government [Administrative Order (AO) No. 200 dated November 21, 1990]

Henceforth, payments made to suppliers should be supported with the necessary documentary requirements particularly the sales invoice.

The Municipal Accounting Office should require the supplier, ConEquip Philippines Inc. to provide the Municipality the necessary warranty security on the equipment procured, either in the form of cash or a special bank guarantee equivalent to at least 1% of the total contract price of P13,853,000.00;

The Municipal Accounting Office should require the supplier, ConEquip Philippines Inc. to pay the necessary withholding taxes amounting to P742,125.00 or any evidence establishing the payment of taxes on the equipment procured.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor as the Local Chief Executive carry out the following:

Exercise proper planning in the identification of beneficiaries and places for which any construction of the PWS would be built to ensure that there is an existing potable and sufficient water source;

Exercise prudence in supervising the execution of the contract in order that any delay and inefficiency in the construction of the potable water system would be prevented;

Ensure that after completion, the project is functional and usable for the purpose it was intended.

To ensure that the resources are managed in the most effective and efficient manner to meet the needs of the constituents and stakeholders of the municipality, we recommended the following:

Carefully plan and organize the project management plan. Often, project planning is ignored in favor of getting on with the work;

Fast track the implementation of unimplemented PPAs;

Evaluate whether the programs and projects funded from prior year’s budget are still relevant, otherwise, revert the fund to other programs and projects which are more needed and applicable upon recommendation of Local Chief Executive and approval by the Sanggunian (Section 322 of RA No. 7160);

The Municipal Development Council (MDC) should strictly monitor and evaluate PPAs (Section 112 of RA 7160) and provide project support or program maintenance/monitoring.

Strictly abide by the provisions of Section 4, Annex A of IRR of RA 9184. Feasibility study and detailed engineering should be mandatory before implementing any project.

